---
import MainLayout from '../../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import MotuSidebar from '../../../components/MotuSidebar.astro';
---

<MainLayout title="CueMix FX Settings">
  <div class="flex gap-8 items-start">
    <div class="w-[250px] flex-shrink-0">
      <MotuSidebar />
    </div>
    <article class="prose max-w-none">
      <h1>CueMix FX Settings</h1>

      <h2>Sample Rate</h2>
      <p>Set the sample rate in CueMix FX (or MOTU Audio Console) before opening your Ableton session. The MOTU clock drives Ableton — both must agree on sample rate.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>44.1 kHz:</strong> standard music production. Best DAW plugin compatibility. Lowest file sizes and CPU load.</li>
        <li><strong>48 kHz:</strong> use when the project will be synced to video or exported for video post-production.</li>
        <li><strong>96 kHz:</strong> recommended for high-resolution recording of the Hydrasynth — captures upper harmonics from wavetable morphing. 2× the data rate of 44.1 kHz.</li>
        <li><strong>192 kHz:</strong> mastering and archival use only; reduces available I/O channel count on the MOTU.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Buffer Size and Latency</h2>
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Buffer Size</th><th>Approx. Latency @ 44.1 kHz</th><th>Recommended For</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>64 samples</td><td>~1.5 ms</td><td>Live performance, real-time monitoring</td></tr>
          <tr><td>128 samples</td><td>~3 ms</td><td>Recording with musicians</td></tr>
          <tr><td>256 samples</td><td>~5.8 ms</td><td>General Ableton sessions</td></tr>
          <tr><td>512 samples</td><td>~11.6 ms</td><td>Mixing with heavy plugin loads</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Start at 256 samples for production work. Reduce to 128 when tracking live instruments or vocals. Drop to 64 only when performing live alongside a drummer or other locked-tempo musicians where even 3 ms matters.</p>

      <h2>Clock Source</h2>
      <p>Set to <strong>Internal</strong> in almost all cases. The MOTU generates its own stable word clock and Ableton slaves to it via the ASIO driver. Only switch to S/PDIF or an external clock source if a dedicated external clock generator is present in the studio.</p>

      <h2>Latency-Free Monitoring</h2>
      <p>This is CueMix's biggest advantage. When recording a vocalist through the SM58:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>In CueMix, route the SM58 input (Input 1) directly to the headphone output bus (Mix 2).</li>
        <li>In Ableton, set the tracking Audio Track's Monitor to <strong>Off</strong>. This prevents the software-path signal from doubling with the CueMix direct monitor.</li>
        <li>The vocalist hears themselves with zero perceptible delay — the signal never touches the computer in the monitoring path.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Saving CueMix Scenes</h2>
      <p>Use <strong>File → Save As</strong> to save complete CueMix FX configurations. Create named scenes for: Tracking (minimal reverb, direct mic monitoring), Production (full bus routing), and Live (standalone mixer layout). Recall any scene in seconds at the start of a session.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
